# Linear issue post-completion workflow

When you finish work on a Linear-assigned issue, complete these post-tasks before ending the session.

## 1. Notify Linear and Slack

Post the same completion summary to both channels.

**Linear:** Add a comment on the issue.

**Slack:** Send to the project's configured channel (or ask the user which channel if unknown).

### Message template

```
✅ **{ISSUE_ID} — {ISSUE_TITLE}** is ready for review.

**Summary:** {1–2 sentence summary of what changed}

**PR:** {PR_URL}

**Recommended follow-up:** {next issue/idea, or "None — no immediate follow-up identified."}
```

Keep the recommended follow-up concrete when there is one (e.g. a related bug, missing test, or natural next feature). Say "None" when nothing stands out.

## 2. Update issue details

Update the Linear issue description with:

### Acceptance criteria (mark complete)

```markdown
## Acceptance criteria

- [x] {criterion 1}
- [x] {criterion 2}
```

### Completion checklist

```markdown
## Agent completion checklist

- [x] Implementation complete
- [x] Tests run (note pass/fail)
- [x] PR opened
- [x] Linear comment posted
- [x] Slack notification sent
```

Add or adjust criteria to match what the issue actually required.

## 3. Update issue status

| When                                    | Status        |
| --------------------------------------- | ------------- |
| Work finished, PR opened                | **In Review** |
| User merges PR or approves after review | **Done**      |

Do not move to **Done** until the user has reviewed the PR. After opening the PR, set status to **In Review** only.

If a follow-up automation watches PR merge (e.g. Cursor Automation with GitHub "PR merged" trigger), that automation may move the issue to **Done** when the PR lands on `main`.

## 4. PR requirements

Every issue that changes code must have a PR before post-tasks are considered complete:

1. Commit and push to a `cursor/<descriptive-name>-6dc1` branch
2. Open a draft PR against `main`
3. Include issue ID (`IIK-xxx`) in the PR title or description
4. Summarize changes and testing in the PR body
